" {TEXT 258 57 "What general formula do the above calculations suggest
?  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 79 "The general formula suggest
ed for the above calculations  is Pascal's Triangle." }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT 297 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 388 "2.  Pascal's Triangle.  \+
Recall the definition of Pascal's Triangle.   Use Maple to construct t
he first 10 rows of Pascal's Triangle. (The trick will be to get the c
oefficients to occur in the correct order.  The Maple command for gene
rating a sequence might be helpful. It is   seq(expression(i),i=m..n);
   where expression(i) is an expression with index i and m..n is a ran
ge of numbers." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 58 "for p from 0 to 10\ndo\nseq(coeff((a+1)^p,a,n
),n=0..p);\nod;\n" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"\"" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"\"F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%
\"\"\"\"\"#F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6&\"\"\"\"\"$F$F#" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6'\"\"\"\"\"%\"\"'F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6(\"\"\"\"\"&\"#5F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6)\"\"\"\"\"'\"#:\"#?F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6*\"
\"\"\"\"(\"#@\"#NF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6+\"\"\"\"
\")\"#G\"#c\"#qF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6,\"\"\"\"\"*
\"#O\"#%)\"$E\"F'F&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6-\"\"\"\"#
5\"#X\"$?\"\"$5#\"$_#F'F&F%F$F#" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3
.  Functions.  In this exericse we study the basic properties of polyn
omials and rational functions.  Some revelant MAPLE commands will be  \+
 factor, expand, solve, fsolve, denom, numer, simplify, subs,   ......
. ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 171 "     The first thing we need to l
earn is how to define a function.  There are two ways, each with its o
wn advantages and disadvantages.  First define the polynomial p1 as " 
}{TEXT 267 2 "a " }{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 268 23 "ymbolic expression in
 x" }{TEXT -1 119 " in the following way:    p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the col
on before the =, this is always required when defining something.)  " 
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "     Now define th
e same polynomial as " }{TEXT 266 30 "an operation on the variable x" 
}{TEXT -1 40 " in the following way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "p2:=x->
x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p2Gf*6#%\"xG6\"6$%)operat
orG%&arrowGF(,&*$)9$\"\"#\"\"\"F1F1!\"\"F(F(F(" }}}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 257 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 190 "Try the following comm
and sequences to see some of the differences in how MAPLE  treats thes
e two definitions.  As always record your observations and comments on
 the worksheet in text mode." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p1;" }{TEXT -1 23 "It is not \+
factoring out" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }{XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%
\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "
p2;" }{TEXT -1 32 "You must tell it to factor for x" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 "6#%#p2G" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p2(x);" }{TEXT -1 42 " You are now t
elling it to factor p2 for x" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%
\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 "
p2(t-3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$),&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"
\"\"\"#F(F(F(F*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p2(u^3-u
^2+2);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$),(*$)%\"uG\"\"$\"\"\"F+
*$)F)\"\"#F+!\"\"F.F+F.F+F+F+F/" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "     \+
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 255 "     This works just like we expect \+
substitution to work because p2 is an operation on whatever is in the \+
(  ).  However since p1 is a symbolic expression we have some difficul
ties with substituting into it directly.   Try the following command s
equences." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
