0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "
5.  Solving Systems of Equations in Several Variables.  " }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 49 "When we have an eq
uation in two variables, e.g.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x -2*y = 5" "6#/,&*
&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 147 "  we o
ften associate with it a graph, the set of points (x,y) in the two-dim
ensional plane which satisfy the equation.  For a linear equation like
 " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x-2*y = 5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%
\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 89 " the graph is a straight line.  For mo
re a complicated equation in two variables, e.g.,  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "2
*x^3 -3*x + y^2 = x*y" "6#/,(*&\"\"#\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$F'F'*&F*F'F)F'!
\"\"*$%\"yGF&F'*&F)F'F.F'" }{TEXT -1 45 "  the graph becomes a more co
mplicated curve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 282 "When we have two equations in two variables, we think of
 the solution set of this system of equations as being the set of poin
ts (x,y) which satisfy both equations simultaneously.  In terms of the
ir graphs, the solution set is the set of points where the graphs inte
rsect (cross).  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 622 "When we have two linear equations in two variables, sinc
e their graphs are straight lines, then two straight lines, if they cr
oss, will cross in exactly one place.  Hence, the solution set of the \+
system of equations will be exactly one point (x,y).  If we have two e
quations which are more complicated, then the number of intersection p
oints (crossing points) of their graphs can vary.  For example, if the
 graph of one equation is a circle and the graph of the other equation
 is a straight line, then, if their graphs cross, then number of solut
ions (intersection points) of the system of equations could be 1 or 2.
  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
128 "We can instruct Maple to find solutions of systems of equations u
sing the solve or fsolve commands.  The syntax for doing so is:" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 30 "     solv
e( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 85 "where eq1 and eq2 are equations in the variables \+
x and y.  This is illustrated below." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" 
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 42 "solve(\{ x + 2*y = 5, 2*x-
3*y = -1\},\{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG#\"#6
\"\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 22 "We could have defined " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 40 "eq1 := x + 2*y = 5;\neq2 := 2*x-3*y = -1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq1G/,&%\"xG\"\"\"*&\"\"#F(%\"yGF(F(\"\"&" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq2G/,&*&\"\"#\"\"\"%\"xGF)F)*&\"\"$F)%\"
yGF)!\"\"F." }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 26 "and then given the command" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
25 "solve( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<
$/%\"yG#\"#6\"\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 55 "and achieved the same result.  Remember t
he solution  (" }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "13/7" "6#*&\"#8\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 2 ", " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "11/7" "6#*&\"#6\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 127 ") represents a point in the two-dimensional plane (why t
wo-dimensional?) where the graphs of the equations intersect (cross). \+
 " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "Find
 the solutions, if they exist, for the following equations " }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.  " }{XPPEDIT 
19 1 "3*x - 2*y = 6" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"
\"\"'" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "4*x + y = -2" "6#/,&*&\"\"%\"
\"\"%\"xGF'F'%\"yGF',$\"\"#!\"\"" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 40 "solve(\{3*x-2*y = 6,  4*x+y = -2\},\{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG#!#I\"#6/%\"xG#\"\"#F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 4 "b.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "6*x -9*y = 12" "6#/,&*&\"\"'\"\"\"%
\"xGF'F'*&\"\"*F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"#7" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3
*y - 2*x = 3" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"yGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"xGF'!\"\"F&" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 41 "solve(\{6*x-9*y = 12, 3*y-2*
x = 3\},\{x,y\});" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 54 "There is no \+
solution, because they are parallel lines." }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "c.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "y = x - x
^2" "6#/%\"yG,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$F&\"\"#!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }{XPPEDIT 
19 1 "y = x-4" "6#/%\"yG,&%\"xG\"\"\"\"\"%!\"\"" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 33 "
solve(\{y = x-x^2,y = x-4\},\{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
